<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18430612-1980">
               <interp inst="t18430612-1980" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18430612"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18430612-1980" type="date" value="18430612"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18430612-1980-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-1980-18430612 t18430612-1980-offence-1 t18430612-1980-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>1980. <persName id="def1-1980-18430612" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-1980-18430612" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1980-18430612" type="age" value="19"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1980-18430612" type="surname" value="MAXWELL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1980-18430612" type="given" value="STEWART"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">STEWART MAXWELL</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18430612-1980-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18430612-1980-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18430612-1980-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="embezzlement"></interp> for embezzlement.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PRENDERGAST</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430612-name-1538" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1538" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1538" type="surname" value="DEFOY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1538" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM DEFOY</persName>
                  </hi>. I an a Custom-house agent, and carry on business in London and in Paris; I was in England at the beginning of March. It was port of the prisoner's business to receive money on my account—Mr. Hall is</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184306120220"></xptr>
               <p>my clerk, and came into my employ a little while before the prisoner—I took the prisoner on his recommendation—I have not received either of the sums in question of the prisoner—it was Mr. Hall's duty to receive from the pri<lb></lb>soner any monies he had received, and the prisoner ought to account to him immediately after receiving it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430612-name-1539" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1539" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1539" type="surname" value="HODSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1539" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES HODSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am clerk to Mr. Prater, an army-clothier, at charing-cross; he occasionally acts as agent for some of his customers in the army. I paid the prisoner, on the 11th of March, 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. on account of Colonel William Ross, for Mr. Defoy.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. HORRY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Had you ever paid part of a bill to Hall, and part to the prisoner? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, and received the prisoner's receipt for the whole—that was the case on the present occasion—I had paid Mr. Hall 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 5<hi rend="italic">d</hi>., two or three days before—this is a receipt for 10<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 4<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 11<hi rend="italic">d</hi>., the full amount of the two sums.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430612-name-1540" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1540" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1540" type="surname" value="ALDERSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1540" type="given" value="ALFRED JOSEPH"></interp>ALFRED JOSEPH ALDERSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am clerk to Mr. Adland. On the 2nd of April I paid the prisoner 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 15<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6 1/2 <hi rend="italic">d</hi>. on account of Mr. Defoy—this is the receipt—the prisoner wrote it in my presence.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Did you give him the whole of the money? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430612-name-1541" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1541" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1541" type="surname" value="VOLTEUR"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1541" type="given" value="JAMES ANTHONY"></interp>JAMES ANTHONY VOLTEUR</persName>
                  </hi>. On the 4th of April I paid the prisoner 3<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 13<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. on account of Mr. Defoy—this is the receipt he gave—it was written in my presence.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Was that sum paid in the whole? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430612-name-1542" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1542" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1542" type="surname" value="HALL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1542" type="given" value="HERBERT WILLIAM"></interp>HERBERT WILLIAM HALL</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the prosecutor's clerk. The prisoner was authorized to receive a sum on account of Colonel Ross, and various sums on account of his master—he has never paid me any sum of money as received on account of Colonel Ross—he has not accounted for a sum received of Adland, and for only 3<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. received from Volteur on the 4th of April—he paid me no sum of money at all on the 2nd April, nor for any received on the 11th of March—he did not mention at the time he paid the 3<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. that he had received any other sum from Volteur—he said Mr. Volteur would not pay any more, our charges were too high.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> How many times were you before the Lord Mayor? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Perhaps six—it may have been ten—the Lord Mayor said the prisoner might go out on bail—my depositions were not taken at the office—I signed none—it was not at my suggestion that I went before the Grand Jury without going before the Lord Mayor—our solicitor brought me here—I do not recol<lb></lb>lect being told to come before the Lord Mayer again—I was not aware that I had to go again—I will swear that the Lord Mayor did not say my accounts were kept in a very suspicious and unsatisfactory manner—he said it would have been better if the prisoner had kept the books himself—he did not say "and not trusted so much to me"—the prisoner did not keep any books himself, he depended entirely on me—on one occasion he gave a receipt in full where I have only received a portion of the money—he was in the habit of paying money over to me and taking no voucher—I was to pay him 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. a week—I have the cash-book here, which will show that I paid him regularly—we were in the habit of going out in company together every evening—we have played twice at skittles—I borrowed 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. of him—I do not remember borrowing 15<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—I paid him—it was two or three months ago—I do not owe him anything—my salary is 70<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. a year—I cannot tell when I returned the 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—I did not talk about paying the night before his apprehension—I do not think anything passed with any one about this 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—it may have happened, and I forgot it—he was generally the collecting-clerk—I have oftener sent him out than gone myself—I do not think he has paid me money above a dozen times since</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184306120221"></xptr>
               <p>Feb.—it may have been a dozen, but not more—nothing passed between me and him about his wages having run in arrears for two or three weeks—I wrote to his father to say that he had misconducted himself, and to send the money up—I wrote a second time, but got no money—I told Mr. Chittle of the prisoner's deficiency, and wanted him to give some money, and it was directly after they refused to give me the money that I took him into custody—that was on the 9th of May—Mr. Prater's was the only one I had found out—this amounted to 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>., and I sent to his father for 6<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 4<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 10<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—I found out the other sums the next morning—the witnesses were all there on the second occasion, and examined—our solicitor applied to have him re<lb></lb>minded—I do not know whether he did on the third occasion.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PRENDERGAST</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you know from the prisoner that he had other money besides the 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. a. week? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, he said he had 15<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. a-week from his father—I wrote for monies he was deficient in on my own account—I did not communicate the deficiency to Mr. Defoy directly I discovered it—I did to the prisoner—he said he would write to his father to send it, and I waited for the result before I told Mr. Defoy—this was at the prisoner's request.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430612-name-1543" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1543" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1543" type="surname" value="HAWKES"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1543" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>CHARLES HAWKES</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-sergeant D</hi> 9.) I apprehended the prisoner, and found a quantity of papers on his person, and this small paper I found in a glove in his pocket.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430612-name-1544" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1544" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1544" type="surname" value="HALL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1544" type="given" value="HERBERT WILLIAM"></interp>HERBERT WILLIAM HALL</persName>
                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. HORRY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Is this your signature to this paper? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No, it is not—this is all my writing, and this too, and this—I did not say, before inspector Black, and other persons, that this was my handwriting.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PRENDERGAST</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Is this which you say is not yours, like yours? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yet, partly—the body of it is in the prisoner's handwriting.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430612-name-1545" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1545" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1545" type="surname" value="DEFOY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1545" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM DEFOY</persName>
                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> I have seen the signature to this paper—I do not believe it to be Hall's—the "L's" appear to have been placed over the letters again by a pen—the others do not—Hall has not hesitated from the first to say that this is a forgery.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Is this other Maxwell's signature? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I believe it is—I first saw it at the Mansion House.</p>
               <p>(The prisoner received a good character.)</p>
               <p>
